Overview¶

Living in the city that is ranked as the second city in the United States, after New York, to have the best food, we felt that looking in the restaurant industry was very fitting. Our dataset is provided by Zomato. Zomato is a food delivery application founded in India in 2008. The application provides information and reviews about restaurants in 24 countries. Using this information, in this project we aim to explore this dataset sourced from Kaggle. Each row in this dataset has information of a restaurant around the world

Our goal in this project is to explore this dataset and evaluate following claims regarding the food industry:

  • (i) Our analysis begins by trying to answer the question: do different parts of the world experience food differently? We establish and explore our claim for a selected number of popular cuisines served across the globe. These cuisines are as follows:
    • American
    • Mexican
    • Italian
    • Indian

  • (ii) Next we will dive into some basic economics and explore the claim that, across the globe, restaurant price structures do not inherently represent food quality. We extend this analysis to different countries and regions (Asia, North America and so on)

    Many examples in our day to day life can represent how higher costs can reciprocate with more value. For example: higher costing cars are usually of a higher value with better engineering features. Higher costs of living in any given geography is usually indirectly or directly reciprocated with more economic opportunities and social utility.

    In this claim we seek to explore the possiblity of whether such a similar viewpoint is also directly or indirectly visible when considering the relationship between food quality and restaurant prices, measured by aggregate ratings and Average cost for two respectively. I.e: is there commonly visible causal relationship restaurant between prices and ratings across the globe? We pursue this analysis using a variety of data visualizaton techniques

  • (iii) Finally we explore a smaller independent claim that focuses on how the extent to which technology is applied across big and small modernized cities in India. We ask the question: Is the increasing modernization of rich Indian cities reflected via tech savvy approaches in the restaurant industry? We apply this analysis by considering whether the frequency of restaurants allowing for online bookings and reservations

Data Wrangling & Preprocessing¶

The raw dataset requires some data processing in order for us to carry our any visual and statistical analysis. In general we will:

  • (i) Represent each country by name based on country code: The raw dataset comprises of country codes uniqly identifying a given country. Although this data is sufficient to carry on any analysis pertaining to countries, representing each country by its name makes it relatively quicker to write code

  • (ii) Represent datapoints by its region: The U.S. Department of Homeland Security breaks the world map into eight distinct geographic regions: Africa, Asia, the Caribbean, Central America, Europe, North America, Oceania and South America. Each of these regions contains a different mix of biomes and geographic features. We would also like to add represent our data on other geographic scales such as by region.

    This allows us to focus our geographic analysis not just by countries but also collectively by regions. For example: grouping the United States & Canada into one group - North America and so on

  • (iii) Standardize all currencies to USD: The Average Cost for two feature value for any given datapoint is in the currency of the country the restaurant is in. We seek to standardize all non-US values to US values to draw conclusions and conduct anaysis on the same scale.

    For instance: Unstandardized restaurant costs in the US vs Indonesia will be incorrect if not normalized since $1USD = IRs. 13,970 therefore making it seem that restaurant prices in Indonesia are significantly higher

  • (iv) Remove Data with Missing Variables: Before starting any analysis it is important to clean your data of any missing variables, because not doing so can significantly influence the conclusions that can be draw from the data

Data Exploration¶

Our dataset, sourced from Kaggle.com, comprises of restaurant data from all over the world. Before we pursue explopring our dataset and highlighting significant insights of the same, we would like to provide brief explanations on our features:

  • Restaurant Id : Unique id of every restaurant across various cities of the world
  • Restaurant Name : Entire name of the restaurant
  • Country Code: Unique code representing the country in which restaurant is located
  • City, Address, Locality, Locality Verbose: General address attributes of the restaurant datapoint.
  • Longitude & Longitude: Longitude & Longitude coordinates of the restaurant's location
  • Cuisines: Cuisines offered by the restaurant. Important to understand that a restaurant can offer multiple cuisines- some of which may not be mutually exclusive. For instance: Italian & Pizza are seperated cuisines in many restaurants
  • Average Cost for two: The mean cost of dining for 2 people in the given restaurant. We use this feature as a reference point for how expensive or cheap a restaurant is in US dollar terms.
  • Currency: The currency in which the Average Cost for two metric is given in. For example: average cost of 2 for a data point in India may be 800 but in terms of Rupees.
  • Has Table booking: Binary (yes/no) datapoint on whether the restaurant allows for reservations
  • Has Online delivery: Binary (yes/no) datapoint on whether the restaurant delivers.
  • Is delivering: Binary (yes/no) datapoint on whether the restaurant is currently delivering
  • Switch to order menu: Binary (yes/no) datapoint on whether the restaurant allows ordering on the Zomato web app.
  • Price range: This metric rages from 1 to 4 and gives a relative understanding of how pricey the food is relative to other restaurants in the city and the country
  • Aggregate Rating: Average restauran rating out of 5. This is a continous variable that can hold any value between 0 and 5. For example: 4.5
  • Rating color & Rating Text: Restaurant rating given in the form of color, text. The distribution is as follows:
    • White : Not rated
    • Red : Poor
    • Orange : Average
    • Yellow : Good
    • Green : Very Good
    • Dark Green : Excellent
  • Votes: Number of ratings casted by people

Ratings Distribution¶

We can observe that the Zomato Restaurants data focus geographically in India and the United States since major cities from these two countries have the highest amount of reviews. Statistically, we would prefer to use the mean when the sample size is large and does not include outliers. Since we are able to catch some outliers, which lie in the pool of "Poor" rating from the boxplot, use the median to describe the middle of a set of data that does have an outlier will be more desirable. So combining the table and the boxplot, we can draw conclusion that Cities have more votes aren't equivalent to have high ratings. For instance, New Delhi, serves as the capital of India, which has the most reviews, but the ratings is around average.

Hypothesis & Analysis¶

Claim 1: Different regions of the world experience food differently¶

We begin our analysis by first evaluating a claim that different regions of the world have different rating distributions for a specific number of cuisines. Through this analysis we explore how different cultures experience food differently. Using the Aggregate rating feature as a 'likability' we explore whether people around the globe like certain types of food in the same way or do some like it more than others? For instance, if the average ratings distribution of Mexican food is shaped similarily in North America & Oceania, we can conclude and support our claim in general countries in these two regions of the world like & experience Mexican food in a similar manner.

Specifically our claim here is that for any given cuisine there will be significant differences in their ratings distributions (and therefore differences in how much people like it in differenr parts of the world). Our selected cuisines to compare across the board are as follows:

  • Cuisine 1: American

  • Cuisine 2: Mexican

  • Cuisine 3: Italian

  • Cuisine 4: Indian

We explore the likability (average ratings) of these cuisines in the following regions: North America, South America, Asia, Africa, Europe & Oceania

Violin Plots - Novel Tufte figure¶

We use violin plots to analyze the rating distributions from shape, center and spread. Using this method of visual analysis gives us insights about rating distributions for a selected number of cuisines from different regions of the world. We will see from the plots how rating distributions do vary in different regions for a certain cuisine. We can observe this variability through the spread of the ratings, density, and some skewness of the distributions.

In general terms, if the shape of the violin plot is more or less similar, i.e: the bulge on top or bottom half is the same for all countries for a given cuisine we can confirm refute our claim that a cusine is liked differently across the globe.

Lastly we would like to briefly explain how our Violinplots as our Novel Tufte figure meets the following requirements:

  • Representation of numbers should match the true proportions.
  • Labeling should be clear and detailed.
  • Design should not vary for some ulterior motive, show only data variation

Based on the visual analysis above we observe the following:

  • American Cuisine: American cusine is appreciated differently across the globe. North America and Oceania have higher likability for American foods. However such is not the case for Asia, Europe and South America. If one were to make a case for each region one could argue that lower ratings distribution of American food in Asian countries can be attributed to the absence of beef. For example: India. Furthermore European cuisine differs widely from American cuisine based on the body parts of livestock consumed. For instance, UK foods comprise liver and intenstine delicacies that are not the norm in the US. This plot allows us to confirm our claim that numerous reasons will account for different regions liking a certain type of food differently.
  • Mexican food: Mexican food is distributed higher and broarder in North America, South America and Africa. The influence of Mecian food on North & South America can be attributed to its close geographic proximity to Mexico. Mexican food influence in the Africas is a pleasant surprise. However this distribution or measure of likability does not hold well in Asia. Perhaps the close yet distinct differences in Asian and Mexican food render it similar to each other in spice and taste. Therefore forgoing the need to establish better Mexican restaurants in the region. Regardless we can continue affirming our claim that Mexican food is not eqivilenty liked across the globe.
  • Italian: Italian food has above average ratings in every region leading us to conclude that it is a cuisine favorited in all regions. This observation alone is enough visual evidence to refute our claim that any give cuisine is likely differently in different parts of the world. The observations cover a wide range in the upper ratings threshold for Italian food.
  • Indian: North America and Europe have relatively concentrated distribution towards rating on Indian Cuisines while Asia has a much wider spread of distribution. The possible reason that why this wide spread of distribution happen in Asia can be the ratio of Asian countries vs datasets. Eight out of fiftheen countries locate in Asia while other continents just have one or two countries. Asia is the biggest continent and contains one of the most diverse cultural elements. People from country in Middle East may view Indian food differently than people from South East Asia in terms of spices that are used, etc. These differences allow us to affirm our claim, for India, that Indian food is not eqivilenty liked across the globe.

Conclusion: We can conclude that our claim cannot be uphelp on account of a mutual and equivilent likabilty for Italian food across the globe. This phenomenon was not observed for different foods. For instance, Mexican cuisine in Asia has relatively wide spread while ratings in Europe generally concentrate between average and good. We also observe that particular type of cuisine being popular in certain region, as the graph shown, Indian food has above average ratings in Africa leading us to conclude that it is a cuisine favorited in this particular region.

Claim 2: Exploring Correlations between Price & Ratings¶

In this section we move on to another independent claim that. In our exploratory analysis we observe a moderate relationship of 0.4 between the Price Range and Aggregate ratings. Using this metric one can inherently establish that there exists a proportional change in one variable given a change in the other. In this section we will exclusively look to refute this observation on a country by country and region by region basis. I.e: we claim that a restaurant's pricing structure is not correlational with its food quality, measured by ratings, across the globe.

As brielfy explained at the beggining of the our analysis, our motivation to evaluate this claim stems from the general viewpoint that in the current day and age higher costs are usually correlated with more reciprocated value. We beleive that this general viewpoint or observation, with regards to relationship between restaurant pricing and its food quality, does not hold at a global level.

We employ the use of visual analysis to pursue our claim:

  • (i) Measure Correlations

  • (ii) Data Concentrations

(i.a) Correlation Analysis - Across Countries¶

Here we will employ the use of scatter plots to observe whether there exists any possible trends positive or negative correlation trends. We choose countries in different areas of the world and try and observe if there exist any causal or non-causal relationships.

From our visual analysis above we can observe the following:

  • United States: In the US there exists a weak but clear correlation between ratings and prices. It is interesting to observe how restaurant pricing for those rated between 3-4 and largely distributed in the average US pricing region between \$20.0 - \\$50. However the distribution of restaurants between ratings 4 and 5 start to slowly trend in the higher pricing region. This phenomenon could convey perhaps that there exists a weak correlation that could perhaps be strengthened should there be a larger dataset for US restaurants.

    When considering the general trend of price vs ratings in the North America region, we observe how the United States follows it.

  • India: The dataset disproprotionally contains restaurant data on India. Unlike in the United States we can see a weaker to non-existent correlation between ratings & pricing and a rather different distribution. For instance there exist more restaurants in the higher price range between \$50.0 and \\$100.0 rated between 3 and 4 than those rated 4 and above. Hence in the case of India there seems to be a very weak relationship between how food quality and pricing

    Unlike North America, Asia shows no promosing correlation at all. The difference between the North American & Asia price vs ratings correlations is the first refute to our claim.

  • Brazil: Brazil's dataset paints a different picture as we can clearly see a stronger correlation between ratings and price. There exist more restaurants in the higher price range between \$50 & \\$60 rated 4 and above than those between 3 and 4 for instance. It is also interesting to note that this correlation will only strengthen as we add more datapoints pertaining to Brazil.

    Brazil follows the South American upward trending relationship between price and ratings.

  • Australia: Australia's scatterplot, although showing a negative correlation, is skewed so by the outlier datapoint in the very high price range rated between 2.5 and 3. Removing this datapoint will show almost no correlation between ratings & prices in this part of the world.

    Lastly, Oceania (comprising of Australia, Indonesia, Fiji & New Zealand) shows a rather different trend to what we observe with Australia as a country. Here we see an upward trend signifying a relatively weak but present non-causal or causal relationship. We can observe here how number of datapoints continue shifting upwards as we move on from one price range to the other after 3.0.

Conclusion: In conclusion our visual anallysis does not support our claim being that the relationship between restaurant prices and its ratings is the same all over the world. We see that restaurant pricing models in Asian countries like India are unaffected by its ratings. Whereas on the other hand North and South American countries may have a truer relationship between prices and ratings such that for the most part, based on our visual analysis, we can say that pricier restaurants may have better tasting food. The differences between Australia and its parent geography entity Oceania also refutes our claim by showing that even within a region the relationships between price and ratings may tend to differ.

Using contour plots, we can establish a strong correlation between 2 variables if the contours flow (or spread) diagonally upwards or downwards based on the other variable present. Using this understanding we can observe the following:

  • North America: We can observe how the contours flow upwards and slightly diagonal followed by a batch of outlier data where the relationship between pricing and ratings follow strongly. We can interpret this contour plot to represent a weak but existing correlation in North America as slowly but surely the contours will flow diagonally as more US based data is considered.

  • Asia: The contours remain relatively flat and flow sideways thus any type of correlation at all.

  • South America: The data flow observed here, except for in the data outlier section for 0 rated restaurants, moves in the upward diagonal direction as the ratings improve. This signifies a much stronger positive correlation between our variables.

  • Oceania: Similarily we observe an upward diagonal flow here but in a more gradual manner, thus signifying a relatively stronger positive correlation between the 2 variables.

Our analysis from the contour plots follow suit with the analysis from scatter plot and help us arrive at the conclusion that we do not have enough evidence to claim that everywhere in the world restaurant prices are unrelated to their ratings.

Claim 3: Narrowing Focus on India¶

In our explanatory analysis we observed how over 90% of this dataset is based in India, given that the data is sourced from an India based web app. Therefore we deemed it appropriate to narrow our third and final claim to India, more specifically to New Delhi, Gurgaon, Noida, and Faridabad, because most of our data is from those regions. These regions can be characterized as being some of the most densely populated, modernized and expensive places in the country. Especially Delhi, it is the capital of India and the second most expensive city to live in within India.

Therefore in this section we explore a relatively uncomplicated claim that moderization in countries such as India is present and can be observed through the use of technology in the restaurant industry. We assume here that the priciest restaurants are most popular, explore where big city restaurants have ways to book a table online or through call ins as well as have online delivery systems in place

Number of Restaurants in Different Cities in India¶

From this graph below, we can confirm that a huge chunk of our data of restaraunts in India is provided from the city of New Delhi. New Delhi is a city in the northern region of India which justifies why North India is the most popular cuisine. The cities ranked after New Delhi are Gurgaon, Noida, and Faridabad. All three of these cities are neighboring cities of Delhi, and often have most people commuting from one city to another. Think of these cities being the Oakland, Foster City, and cities in South Bay to San Francisco.
